segments.text: The amount that went to each of them was not readily identifiable by anybody at the legislative level, but of course it was internally because of the way we put the budgets together with Dean Benson.
And before he retired, we did change our budget structure, so we separated the two and each of us go in with our own budget request like each of our other system partners now.
And then when Mr. Rutter dies in early 1970, Jack Williams comes in later that year, John Calhoun as vice president, did TTI's role change under them?
Not really.
We still, let's see, I guess Fred was what he was...

vice president for engineering he carried several titles during this period of time and we still reported through Fred even to Calhoun and then later to Calhoun himself under a different structure I've got a list of all the different people that I've reported to and I think there were 17 different ones on that list of fellows
of who we have really reported to.
But anyway, there is a bunch of turnover in the system and in university as well.
We've reported both ways from time to time.
Fred had always been a supporter, of course.
And even after he became dean and Jack Case was director, all budget matters went through Fred.
We went in with the joint budget of TTI,
and civil engineering because he was responsible for all of those.
And he made the final decisions, or at least asked questions such that you made the decision the way he would like to have it made, I think, in most of those cases.
Did any key campus administrator in your memory ever question the importance of TTI?

I know I can't immediately say, yes, it was Joe Smith that did this, but that we have had the question raised, and I don't know at what level or really the background behind it, but why should we be devoting particularly prior to this last legislative session, particularly to campus facilities,
to an organization that really has no academic teaching responsibilities.
And it's never been made a major issue.
But up until the last session of the legislature, it was always sort of a little burr under the saddle there.
Now, of course, we are getting appropriations directly to offset those, and it's a pass-through.
We get the appropriation and pass it through to the university for facilities and maintenance and upkeep and all those sorts of things.
All right.
Today, TTI reports to whom?
Today, the director reports directly to the chancellor.
No to the minute they may have changed that.
I think that I think that now and this has been quite.
and I'm sorry to be vague on this, but I've been out of it now for a little while.
I think now it's reporting to our vice president for engineering, which is also head of the T's.
You mean vice chancellor?
Vice chancellor, yeah.
When did it become then a system component instead of a campus component?
It was a system component in 1950.
Oh, so it always was.
Always has been.
Oh, okay.
All right.

Now, there were questions raised about that as to whether the board could officially designate, which they had done, could officially designate and create a system component for that action of the legislature.
And that was resolved back in the 80s.
Looking back, let's see, trace the directors who, after Keyes, who?
Me.
And you, what year?
Well, Jack Keyes had a heart attack in the fall of 1975.
I took over.
Fred called me in and said, Jack's going to be out a year sort of helping run the place now.
Do you want to continue doing that, and do you want me to change your title to

interim director or something like that and i said the current title is fine i'm associate director at the time i didn't do everything i could do as interim i mean associate that i don't see any point in changes okay we'll just wait and change it in the next budget cycle so officially it was the uh then the beginning fall of 76 until 93 had 17 years
During those years, summarize how the employee workforce and the budget went from what to what.
We started out, during those years, we had begun growing.
And when I started my tenure as director, we probably had a budget of about $10 million a year, I would assume.

uh when i retired we were at 39 million i believe so we agree we had a rather fast growth spurt uh primarily because opportunities were there and nothing brilliantly that i did to make that happen it's just that we had a bunch of good people and we had some good opportunities to to to get into some new areas that were growing areas such that we've had to accommodate
a number of our people in off-campus lease space over the years.
In fact, our new building that we just got built out here now, we took 34,000 square feet of lease space that moved all those people in this building out in the research park.
So we were able to pay the building out of the
most good part of the building cost out of that money we were paying for leases outside, and we'll have a building that leads through.
So that's worked out very well.
Of that, in your, that $39 million, about what percentage or what sum was private enterprise and what was state appropriation?
Okay, two different, there's three different categories.
Private enterprise, that is the private sector, very small.
I'd say always in less than 10%.
State appropriations running from 10 to 12%, and the rest of it all comes from other governmental sources.
The Federal Highway Department, Federal Highway Administration, other states, their own state.
But you all have to compete for that.
Yes, that's all competitively bid contract research work.
So that in terms of state appropriation, out of that $39-40 million,
Four, five, six million were?
Up until I retired, the biggest we'd ever gotten, I believe, was $1.2 million of state appropriated money.
And the employee workforce?
It's about, well, our total, the number that we use now, this is about 650 now.
But that includes about 250 students, about equally split between undergraduate and graduate students.
most of them are majoring in?
Well, you'd think they'd be majoring in civil engineering, but they're not.
They're majoring in practically everything.
Computer science, engineering's a big one, of course.
We've got economists, economics in there.
We've got a number of them from over in the social sciences.
We do a lot of work in our roadside safety area about driver behavior.
workload, this whole issue of talking on the frazzling telephone while you're driving down the road or looking at the onboard computer while you're driving down the road.
So we have a number of human factors to graduate and undergraduate students as well.
In your years as the director,
summarize some of the work that you all did.
Of all of the projects that you all did that you were closely involved in, of which ones are you most proud?
I guess the first one, because it is so visible and is so intense in a way, is our roadside safety programs, where we have now developed
roadside safety appurtenances materials that have saved literally thousands and tens of thousands of lives and untold economic benefits.
We figured that about $7 billion worth of economic costs have been saved by

people not getting killed and not getting seriously injured when they hit guardrails or run off the road in areas that are hitting one of the big overhead signpost structures that we've made breakaway and have treated safety.
So we've been very proud of the work that we've done and are still developing that area, doing quite a bit of work.
Another thing that we're very proud of in that area is that we, that is one of the few things that we've been able to take to the private sector
and have them, through licensing agreements, we have licensed this technology.
They're building it, putting it out on the roadway, and we get a very handsome royalty from that.
So the money gets recycled.
So we get to recycle the money.
This year, last year, by the way, that's what I do now is handle intellectual property.
So that's the one thing I can talk about currently.
But last year, we made, in royalty payments, over $2.5 million off the oversight safety program.
So of the current budget, 5%?
Mm-hmm.
All right, other projects that you're very proud to look back on and claim?

I guess the other one would be it's not quite as visible, but the work that we've been doing and have become, I think, international leaders in is in the materials area, the roadway materials area more than anything else.
Here we're trying to incorporate the chemical engineering profession into the civil engineering work

of how do you characterize in a meaningful way the materials that you're putting into the roadway but in recent years we have found out that it's not only you know asphaltic roadway things not only the asphalt it's also the different kinds of aggregate you get one aggregate that's got certain characteristics it will interact in a horrible way with material with other with another set of characteristics so you have to
be able to identify not only what you're putting in and the physical quality, but you have to get to the chemical quality of the interfaces of those different materials.
And we've developed a lot of work in recycling old materials to use them, and sometimes they make even better roadways than you would make out of the original raw materials.
What are the most interesting discoveries you all have made in those materials?
Which would be the most surprising materials?
I think the biggest one, because it's the biggest use that's been made out there, is in the asphalt area.
And there, to characterize and to try to overcome the traditional...

knowledge that everybody had that asphalt was a single material and the fact that if you took an eight physically we have always characterized asphalt by a number uh if it has a certain hardness and this is what they really go by it goes but get an ac5 and ac10 and ac20 each of those is a different hardness of asphalt and that means that it'll go through a tube under a certain set of temperatures and then a certain speed
And if it's an AC-5, then you put it with these things.
But what we've really found is that's not the case.
That's not the problem that we're solving.
We're trying to do it with physical measurements, and we have to do it with better measurements than we've ever done before.
Because even though the Romans were able to build roadways that lasted forever, practically, they built it in a way that we can't afford to build them now.
The Europeans are building roadways that are much better than

we're doing because they have developed and again a very expensive process but one that lasts a long time it's a very good system where they contact aggregate on aggregate contact on larger aggregates and as long as you have the load bearing on a set of aggregates that are contacting another aggregate rather than a soft piece of asphalt it's not going to rut or ravel out like the other materials do we've not got it all
incorporated into the construction processes, but not everybody, not all of the states really believe it yet.
That's one of the things that's going to be, I think, a big lifesaver, because it's a money saver.
All right, now let's go to the other extreme.
Among the most frustrating efforts y'all have been involved in.
Getting acceptance, I guess, of some of the human factors considerations in transportation.
The whole issue of trying to marry technology with the ability of the human and its ability to assimilate and accumulate the knowledge that has been presented to them.
Traditionally, you as a driver or I as a driver of an automobile going down the roadway, we're focused on
The roadway itself, the oncoming vehicles, the conditions, whether it's raining or dry or whatever, but we're conditioned on a fairly narrow set of outside influences that we have to deal with.
Now, you put an onboard computer in that's going to do all this marvelous stuff for you if you're lost and tell you where you are and how to get back to where you are.
and give you a cell phone at the same time.

I just saw an announcement or a statistic yesterday of a study that was done, I've forgotten exactly what it was now, but if you're using a cell phone in an automobile, your probability of being involved in a serious accident is 400% of what you would have without that.
We've been believing that for a long time,
And they've been involved in trying to get this human factor overload, or human overload, mental overload system recognized as a real problem.
And I think it's not only a problem in automobile transportation, it's a problem in air transportation as well.
I think they've recognized it a lot quicker than we have.
Have there been any proposals, requests, suggestions to TTI that were truly goofy?
Absolutely.
Such as?
We get solutions to problems all the time.
We had a fellow from Houston that came up with a total set of drawings, all of which he had stamped as very private and confidential.
really wanted us to sign a confidentiality agreement before we would look at them and we wouldn't do it.
But when you opened it up and looked at what he was proposing, he was going to have a low friction transportation system in the city of Houston.
He was going to have every roadway coming into the city of Houston built at a downward angle.
And he was going to have a machine up here that built ice cubes
And rather than having rolling rubber tires, you would put these ice cubes under your car and down that.
And, you know, what sort of a nut house did this guy come out of?
But those are, that's fairly extreme.
But we do get, I'm looking at one right now where a fellow's got a new system for, he thinks, for the trucking industry.
That...
I think is a pipe dream of what he would like to do.
It's segmenting the delivery system for goods movements.
And what it ends up being is doing the same thing we're doing now already, except it's not patented materials.
And so it's available to everybody.
Every Safeway store has a system of moving from this warehouse to distributing their goods.
And they worked on it for a long time.
50 years to get it done right.
You all have worked with a lot of corporations.
I'm not going to ask the negative.
Which corporations in TTI's work, to which corporations would you give the highest marks of excellence?
I'd have to give it to Trinity Industries, which is a local Texas organization.
And they are our primary licensee on our roadside safety work.
They've done an excellent job.
They partnered, they wanted to be partners with them.
We have to, if anything, we have to sort of push them back and say, now we can't be that good a partner.
I mean, that's strong a partner because there are certain things of competitive nature we have to assure that we're being fair to everyone else.
But they have been a very good partner.
They have been...
not only accepting of what we do, but they've been participating and helping fund a lot of the stuff that we do, and for which they then compete for the license for.
They do still have to compete for the licensing.
And have you all done work for non-Texas, or is that not part of your charter?
Oh, yeah, we do work for non non Texas.
In fact, we do a lot a lot of work for other states.
A lot of safety work for other states.
We do a lot of federal work, not as much now as we did, say five years ago.
Because
We have never really gotten real good at the political process of earmarking funds at the federal level.
And in the last two bills, that's been a really, really big problem.
They come out with a great big research program and it's all earmarked.
So much goes to Idaho, so much goes to, you know, set up a
recycling center in, not in Connecticut, next state over.
Rhode Island?
Yeah, Rhode Island.
But where they had no, they've had no experience at all in doing any of that sort of work.
But they've set them up because of their strength of the political processes in Washington.
And we've not been very good at that.
Have there been any state or federal elected officials that have been particularly good friends of TTI?
State officials, yes, they have.
Our own officials have been very, very good to us.
Are there some that deserve special mention?
Well, I think that...
to the extent that they can, and some of them are not in the positions yet to do so, that Ogden has been very interested in the work that we've done.
Senator Steve Ogden.
But go back in the past.
Back in the past, Ray Barnhart was a very strong supporter.
He became head of the Federal Highway Administration.
Of course, Tiger Tate and Jake Pickle
They were willing to support us and the University of Texas as long as we didn't get one really out of balance with the other.
But Tiger was always a good, strong supporter of TTI.
Has it made much difference in TTI's life whether there is a Democrat or Republican governor in Texas?
Yes, it has.
In recent years, I don't know how much to say about this.
Well, who's been most supportive?
We won't do the negative.
The Republican Party has been much more supportive of the research program and of the overall need for transportation research and transportation-related work in the transportation system.
Now, Kay Bailey Hutchison, Senator Hutchison at the federal level, has been a good friend and...
I mean, we don't have a whole bunch of stuff sitting on our desk of request, and Phil Graham has.

To the extent that Phil is not normally, Senator Graham is not normally one who says, yes, I will go in and support this, and regardless of the cost of the program, you know, it's, well, I don't really like to put the federal money in it, but if there's any that comes into it, I'll sure try to see you get your share of it sort of approach.
All right, as you look back on all these years, what were your proudest, with TTI, what were your proudest moments?
Mostly I think it's been things that other people have done, really, that have been associated with TTI.
We've had some very, very excellent people
that have gotten awards for activities that they've been involved in or developments or research that they have done.
We have some aboard now, like we started the Center for Aggregate Research.
This is one of those areas to talk about.
And Dr. Dallas Little is a professor of civil engineering and has been one of our employees for 20-something years and is an absolutely outstanding young man, or not young man.
Of course, to me, he's still a young man, but he's done a great work.
Dr. Hirsch, Teddy Hirsch, has done some excellent work that's gotten some real recognition on the work that he's done in the roadside safety area.
Developed the first breakaway highway sign work that was a real killer and was
almost immediately adopted by the Federal Highway Administration as a requirement on all interstate roads.
So we've had some really good work done that I've been very proud that our people have been involved in and they've done.
If you were looking back on all these years related to A&M, whether with TTI or not, we're on the downhill slope now.
To whom would you feel greatest appreciation?
If everybody could walk in the room from those years, whom would you want to thank most?
Obviously, one of the first ones would be Fred Benson.
I always admired Fred's forthrightness and his ability to cut to the heart of the matter and his willingness to make decisions and stand by and make decisions when
It might be more convenient to form a committee to make the decision for you.
Of course, in one of the cases when he hired me as director, appointed to move me up as director, his total interviewing process was, Jack Case is gone,
I'd like to be, you'd be the new director.
Would you like to have a job?
And I said, yes, he said, okay, we'll start it first.
And that was, I mean, we didn't go through a committee and didn't have to have a whole lot of other people's input.
He knew what he wanted to do and how he wanted to do it and was willing to do it on his own, on his own responsibility.
Today, we take six months.
Don't we?
Haskell, we are killing ourselves.
We are absolutely killing ourselves.
And the end result is not as skillfully done.
You're absolutely right.
What you get is, you may not want this, but in my view, what we do, we form committees to go in.
We make the poor candidate come in and go through this committee.
What you're looking for is how many negatives do you get.

And if you don't like this and you don't like that, pretty soon you get down to somebody down here where nobody finds anything they don't like about him, but there's nothing really good about him either.
They're comparatively bland.
They're right.
It's absolutely right.
All right, other people that you'd want to thank beyond Fred Benson?
Well, of course, the old-timers.
Mr. Gilchrist, of course, because of his longstanding...

involvement and leadership in this in this whole area jack keese jack keese was a good leader jack keese was a better leader he was he was a good researcher but he was primarily a leader instead of a researcher and i think he did his best work that way so i never want to thank i want to thank him in
Well, of course, there's a whole bunch of other people that I think have done an excellent job as far as their involvement with TTI.
But I'm thinking about it up in the system and university level, or university system level.
Those are the two primary ones.
I'm sure I'm leaving out somebody that I just can't think of at the moment.

And the chancellors from the time the system is recreated with following William's heart attack, which of those chancellors, I'm not going to ask the negative ghetto, which of those chancellors would you give the highest marks to?
We're talking about from roughly 77 to now.
77 to the time I, yeah.
Now, right now, down to the point, I'm having a hard time remembering who were the names.
Well, Hubert Mobley.
Frank Hubert was a good one.
a supporter of ours, and was trying to, I think he tried to be helpful in every way he could.
I mean, he was never anything negative.
I'm trying to think who after Mobley, was there anybody between Mobley and Thompson?
I don't think so.
Oh, okay.
I've got my list in there somewhere.
But, and of course, I've always had a high respect for Mobley.
For Thompson, he did not have a whole lot to do with TTI, but at the time he was in there, he was a strong supporter of TTI.
He particularly liked that we were trying to do something practical and helpful for the people who were trying to serve in the state of Texas.
